animal.name: Fanta
animal.description:
Spunky puppy with a big loving heart!
Hi! My name is Fanta. I'm shy at first around humans but warm up to people faster than you would expect. I am very spunky and will play with dogs of any size! I love to play hard, nap hard and then repeat! I listen well and am learning my basic cues. I am an excellent eater and do mealtime easily with my foster siblings. I don't like walks as my confidence is not high enough yet, but I am curious about trying. I am crate and potty trained, but I am a puppy still and have the occasional accident. My ideal forever home would have a fenced in backyard. Another dog to play with is a must. I'd love a patient family to help build my confidence. Older children, 13 years old and up, are best.

General socialization notes:

 I'm shy at first, but warm up quickly with a little patience. Once warmed up, I love belly rubs and head scratches from people. I love other dogs and I learn a lot from them. I like praise more than treats as rewards when learning.I am crate trained and if you grab my crate Kong, I go right in. When you get home, it might take me a minute to come out after opening the door.

Does Fanta like other pets?

Yes, I love other dogs and would do best in a home with another dog or multiple dogs. I play with my foster brother for hours at a time to get nice and exhausted. Then I take long naps to recharge for more play time. I have limited experience with cats and did fine with them.

Does Fanta like children?

Small children move too fast and might scare me. I'd do best in a home with children 13 years old and older.

Favorite toys:

I love pretty much all toys, but really like Kongs and antlers. I will de-stuff soft toys if given the chance, but I don't eat the stuffing.

Ideal forever home:

 I'll do best in a home with a patient family and other dogs. I am learning a lot from my foster siblings and will continue to learn with you. I'd love a fenced in backyard to be able to run and play in. I'd be fine with cats. I'd be okay with children 13 years old and older.

animal.name: Richard aka Rico
animal.description:
Hi! My name is Richard, but my foster mom calls me Rico. I've been through some tough stuff in my life, so I am slow at trusting people. What can I say? I'm just picky and want to surround myself with only the bestest of friends. Could that include you? I'd need a home with another dog and cats would be okay too! A home with children 10 years old and up would be best.

General Socialization Notes:

 My foster mom says I'm super smart and can learn new stuff pretty quickly. You just need to have lots of treats handy, as I am extremely food motivated. I know how to sit, lay down, shake, give high fives, wave, and touch. I'm working on stay, place, leave/drop it, and loose leash walking skills and am making great progress! I also love hanging out in my crate because I see it as my own personal safe space.
I absolutely LOVE LOVE LOVE going on walks! When my harness and leash come out, I get so excited! Getting out into the world to explore and adventure with my favorite person is my idea of a good time. I also love riding in the car because it often means I'm going somewhere for a walk!


Does Richard like other pets?

 My high energy is unmatched. I could play for HOURS and never get sick of it. Though I'm slow to trust humans, I adore my fellow doggy friends. I would prefer a home with another high energy dog so we could play and play and play! In my foster home, I live with a female rescue who also loves to play. We spend our days running around in the yard, chewing on each other, and wrestling. I love being with her! I can be a little pushy when playing, but I'm also getting better at knowing when my playmate is tired and needs a break.
Playing is my passion, so much so that I even often try to play with my foster mom's cats. I know they are small, so I approach as carefully as I can, but they still hiss at me. That's okay though. I know the hiss means I should leave them alone. But maybe I can try again later? Foster mom is so proud of me for how well I can interact with the kitties. I also spend time in her bedroom with her rats and I like those guys too!

Does Richard like children?

Another thing you should know about me is that I like routine and knowing what to expect. Because of this, I don't think I'd feel very comfortable in a home with little kids, as I know they can be pretty unpredictable. I live with a nine-year-old girl in my foster home, but she's pretty calm and leaves me alone. I like that energy, but I know most other kids are different.

Favorite Toys:

My favorite toys are basically anything I'm not supposed to play with. I prefer playing with paper products around the house, but I'm slowly learning how to appreciate my stuffed toys instead. I also like playing with snuffle mats, puzzle toys, and frozen kongs, but can get bored with them after a while. I need someone who can keep me active and entertained throughout the day!

Ideal Forever Home:

 I'dlove a quiet home where not many visitors come through. Once I've adjusted to my routine, change can be scary for me. Plus, as I mentioned, I'm fearful of new people, so I'd rather just spend a lot of time with the family I already know and trust.I know I can be antisocial, but I can be a total cuddle bug with the right person. So far, I only fully trust one person, but I'd like to have more friends. Show me patience and understanding, and I'm sure I'll come to love you Please consider giving me a chance to be your new best friend!

animal.description:

I am not good with cats or small furry creatures. I eat alone or in my crate and would have to take it slow if I eat with a future brother or sister. I am looking for my furever' home where I can give you all the love I have in my heart, which is as big as my pibble head! Up to date on shots, chipped and neutered.

Doc believes I’m 10-12 years old. Don’t let the blind/deaf disability turn you away. It doesn’t impact me — except sometimes I bonk into stuff. 

The rescue believes I’m Chihuahua mix.

-I enjoy rides in the stroller and short walks outside ???

-Fine with cats ?
-I’m not sure how I am with small humans (kids) based on how easy going I am I think it would be no problem ??????
-I’m great in the car ?
-I don’t mind my crate and I’m ok at sleeping there at night but would love to snuggle in bed as long as I’m safely up there. I don’t want to fall off ?
-My foster family says I’m the best/easiest going guy. They sometimes forget I’m here. I just need a second chance and a great place to snooze 20+ hours a day for the rest of my life??

animal.name: Tallie
animal.description: Tallie is an active Red Australian Shepherd about 5 years old. She was part of a hoarding case, living outdoors with minimal care or shelter. She has blossomed into a lovely attentive, active gal , eager to go and do whatever you are willing to take her for.  She rides well in the car, and likes to hitch a ride on the ATV going for chores. She has been good with the other similar sized dogs in her foster home but her antics can be a bit much for small dogs. Tallie sleeps in a large sized crate at night, comes when called reliably, stays behind a fence,  is not a digger or a barker but is showing she knows her yard and will bark at the Fed eX guy making our Chewy.dom delivery! She is a genuine companion and wants attention and to be loved on. Tallie had an old eye injury in her left eye when we got her and she has limited or no vision in that eye but the veterinarian did a thorough check and found no scratches or infection and Tallie has learned to compensate for that most of the time. On occasion you will notice she bumps into something on that side.  But it does not slow her down, she is interested in fetching, does great with livestock, responds well to direction and has good recall.  Likes plush toys and antllers to chew on and loves the water and her wading pool! Good on leash and off. Tallie's best home would be an active,  person, couple or family with older kids that have some previous dog training experience to help Tallie continue to learn what living in a home is,   willing to accomodate her sight limitations and keep her safe while giving her the love and time she so deserves.  Tallie is fostered in Lamar, CO and will be adopted from her foster home.

animal.name: Charlie
animal.description: Charlie is a lovely purebred Cavalier King Charles Spaniel about 8 years old. She is sweet as can be and loves to be with you, in her doggie bed napping or just chilling. Charlie was found by a fisherman at a remote reservoir during a rainstorm. She was filthy, matted and her eyes were almost matted shut. She has a microchip but no amount of searching or investigative work was able to turn up an owner. We have had Charlie awhile, treating her for eye infection, health issues, and a heart murmur. Charlie is stable now and really enjoying life! She is good with other dogs, does well in the house, sleeps in her crate  at night and will search out her crate when she is sleepy during the day, so the door is open or will sleep in a dog bed. Charlie rides well in the car and likes a snuggle on the couch in the evening. Likes to be carried and not a squirmer. We think she might have been a breeding dog and does carry some of the maladies of the breed. Charlie has dry eye and a heart murmur both manaaged well with medicine which has an out of pocket expense of about $70 a month. She takes her medicine well/easily too. The dry eye and the eye infection she had when we found her has left her short sighted, but she compensates by air scenting for you when outdoors. Her hearing is negligible but for all her shortcomings she is a lovely, ever so sweet and always HAPPY, HAPPY HAPPY  little dog. Cutest snufflely snore ever!  She does well with the older dogs in her foster home and looks to them for whats going on and will lie quietly in the sun together  or follow them around outdoors. Charlie also follows you around, but can lose sight of you so she requires an attentive human and safe yard for her safety.  Happiest dog ever! A quieter home, willing and able to provide for her medical needs, with no small children or active dogs that can run over her is  a must. Fostered in Lamar CO and will be adopted out of her foster home.

animal.description:
Meet Arlo! Arlo is an amazing dog who was found on the streets of Houston and taken to the city pound. He joined the Joyrides family and is now blossoming in his foster home! Arlo loves walks, people, head scratches and treats! He is instant friends with everyone he meets and at home he is calm, low-key and quiet. Although when he does get excited (dinnertime!) he does the cutest little hops! Sounds about perfect! Arlo can be shy in new situations and is looking for a family who will be patient with him and provide him reassurance as he builds up his confidence. Arlo is pretty ambivalent about dogs (he basically ignores them) - but dislikes dogs who are ill-mannered and pushy. He will do best as an only dog or in a home with another low-key dog who isn't looking for a playmate. If you'd like to meet this handsome boy, email info@joyrides.org to request an app!

Arlo is being fostered in Houston, TX. He would come to his new home via professional transport. 

Age : 5-6 yrs
Weight: 60 lbs
Needs fenced in yard? Not necessarily
Dogs: Best with calm, older dogs
Cats: no cats please!
Kids: Would do best with adults/older kids because he can get scared at times with loud noises
Energy level (scale of 1-10): 4
Vaccinated: yes
Spayed/Neutered: yes
Microchipped: yes
Other considerations: Arlo needs a patient family who understands he's still getting used to being safe!

animal.name: Pierre
animal.description: Hello everyone, this is little Pierre.  When the rescue brought me this joyful little bundle of adorable puppyness, they told me his mother was an Akita but the didn't know what Dad was.  I searched the internet for pictures of mixed breed Akitas to see if any of them looked similar but none of them did.  I'm not one to give up easy so I continued searching for pictures that looked like this little ball of happy furry teeth.  I believe I have now discovered the truth of their paternal lineage.... this littler of pups is clearly a cross between an Akita and a Red Fox.  For some reason the rescue keeps telling me that this isn't possible, something about "genetics" and "science", but I'm pretty sure I'm right.  Come see any of the puppers from this litter and decide for yourself ?
